<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">41547577</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>19</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>19</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1532-8422</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>40</Volume><Issue>4</Issue><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Apr</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Journal of cardiothoracic and vascular anesthesia</Title><ISOAbbreviation>J Cardiothorac Vasc Anesth</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Anatomic Profiles Related to Transesophageal Echocardiographic Probe Insertion: A Retrospective Computed Tomographic Analysis.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>1091</StartPage><EndPage>1096</EndPage><MedlinePgn>1091-1096</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1053/j.jvca.2025.12.019</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S1053-0770(25)01233-9</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="OBJECTIVES" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">To clarify the anatomic relationship between the larynx and the esophageal inlet relevant to transesophageal echocardiography (TEE) and to identify structural factors associated with probe-related injury.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="DESIGN" NlmCategory="METHODS">A retrospective observational study based on computed tomography (CT).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="SETTING" NlmCategory="METHODS">A single center in Japan.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="PARTICIPANTS" NlmCategory="METHODS">A total of 180 consecutive patients who underwent intraoperative TEE between 2023 and 2025 and had preoperative CT, including the cervical region.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="INTERVENTIONS" NlmCategory="METHODS">None. CT images were reviewed to determine the inlet orientation angle and the minimal distance between the cricoid cartilage and vertebral body (retrocricoid space).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="MEASUREMENTS AND MAIN RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">The inlet orientation ranged from -17.8&#xb0; to +33.3&#xb0; (mean, +2.9&#xb0;). A posterior inlet was identified in 179 of 180 patients (99.4%), with 1 posterolateral and no lateral orientation. The retrocricoid space measured 1.4 to 13.4 mm (mean, 6.3 mm) and was narrower than the shaft diameter of a TEE probe (&lt;10 mm) in most patients. Additional CT findings included calcification of the posterior cricoid lamina (7.8%), unilateral vertebral protrusion (3.3%), and spinous bony projections (2.8%). These data indicate that the inlet is almost always posterior. A narrow retrocricoid space or rigid posterior structure may increase local wall stress during blind insertion.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">CT imaging has demonstrated that the esophageal inlet lies posterior to the larynx in nearly all patients. When resistance is encountered, the probe should be advanced along a slightly oblique 5- or 7-o'clock trajectory with gentle rotation and anteflexion. These findings provide an anatomic basis for standardized TEE training and injury prevention.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2025 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Orihashi</LastName><ForeName>Kazumasa</ForeName><Initials>K</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Kochi Medical School, Kohasu Oko-cho, Nankoku, Kochi, Japan. Electronic address: orihashik@kochi-u.ac.jp.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType><PublicationType UI="D064888">Observational Study</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2025</Year><Month>12</Month><Day>23</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>United States</Co